Former Banyana Banyana striker Portia Modise remains the leading goal scorer on the African continent for both men and women netting over 100 goals. eNCA reporter Tshepo Thobane discussed the support for women's football in the country with her. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Former Banyana Banyana captain Portia Modise lifts the lid, on what it’s like to be a female football player in South Africa. In her recently launched book, Modise highlights the pay disparity between male and female players. WATCH | In conversation with former Banyana Banyana captain Amanda Dlamini And according to her, the women’s national team performs far much better than the men’s. Modise said, “I'm trying to reach out to South Africans in different ways so that people listen to what we say because we don’t have enough platforms to talk our experiences." "The unfairness in women's football and people are quick to judge because you know women are being looked as objects in this country so that’s why when you see a woman try to raise their voice it's like we don’t deserve better equality." "Me deciding to write a book I know that you cannot ignore it forever. At some point, there are those who will listen and will make a difference."